---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="What Decks Really Cost in Maryland (2026) | Belvedere Decks"
  description="Real 2026 deck pricing: new composite boards $14k–$20k, boards plus railings $24k–$35k, new custom decks $40k–$75k+. What moves the number and what a cheap bid leaves out."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Published pricing for 2026</p>
      <h1>What decks really cost.</h1>
      <div class="rule"></div>
      <p class="lead">
        Most deck companies won't put prices in writing until they've sat in your
        kitchen. Here's what projects actually run in Maryland in 2026.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <table class="stack">
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <th><a href="/services/deck-resurfacing">Deck Resurfacing: boards only</a></th>
            <td>Every deck board replaced with premium composite. Your frame and railings stay. <strong>$14,000–$20,000</strong> for typical 300–400 sq ft decks.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th><a href="/services/deck-resurfacing">Deck Resurfacing: boards + railings</a></th>
            <td>Everything you see and touch is new: boards, railings, and edge trim on your existing frame. <strong>$24,000–$35,000</strong> around 400 sq ft.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <th><a href="/services/new-deck-builds">New Deck Builds</a></th>
            <td>A fully custom new deck: designed, engineered, permitted, and inspected. Includes tear-out of an old deck where needed. <strong>$40,000–$75,000+</strong>.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>Our projects start at $5,000. We don't take on small repairs.</p>

      <h2>What moves the number</h2>
      <p>
        Size. Board line: we install TimberTech and Trex, from entry to architectural
        grade. Railing choice. Stairs and lighting. Height off the ground. And the one
        nobody mentions: the condition of the frame underneath. That's why we inspect
        before we quote, and why joist replacement has a written allowance in your
        contract instead of becoming a surprise charge later.
      </p>

      <h2>What should make you suspicious</h2>
      <p>
        A bid thousands below everyone else usually means no permit, no waterproof
        flashing where the deck meets the house, support boards spaced too far apart for
        composite decking, or railings screwed to the boards instead of bolted to the
        frame. Those are exactly the things you can't see at the barbecue, and pay for
        in year five.
      </p>

      <div class="notice">
        <strong>Every price we quote includes:</strong> footings dug to code depth, full
        waterproof flashing at the house, steel connectors with every fastener hole
        filled, permits and inspections where required, haul-away of all debris, and a
        10-year written workmanship warranty on top of the 25–50-year manufacturer board
        warranties.
      </div>

      <h2>How our pricing compares</h2>
      <p>
        High-end design firms in this market publish composite pricing starting around
        $30,000 and running $120–180 per square foot installed. Budget operators
        advertise numbers that quietly leave out the structure. We land in between on
        purpose: premium specification at an honest number, with the math shown.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-top: 24px;"><a class="btn primary" href="/estimate">Get a Free Estimate</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
